A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
This program funds activities at the Cyber Resiliency Office for Weapon Systems (CROWS). The CROWS is the sole organization tasked to enhance and enable
Department of the Air Force (DAF) Program Acquisition Executives (PAEs) and Program Management Offices (PMOs) to understand, engineer, and integrate cyber
resiliency into emerging and fielded weapon systems, to mitigate critical cyber-based vulnerabilities, and preserve mission effectiveness in contested environments.

The CROWS' mission directly aligns with the National Defense Strategy (NDS). The NDS specifically emphasizes deterring and defending against cyber threats as
vital to safeguarding the U.S. homeland and military from aggression and strategic attacks by building a resilient, survivable Joint Force in the cyber domain, which
requires the Department of War to prioritize investments in cyber defense, resilience, and the continued integration of cyber capabilities into the full spectrum of military
operations.

This program addresses weapon system cyber resiliency through several system security engineering focused activities. A notable activity is to develop systems
security engineering tools, techniques, and procedures, with associated training and education, to integrate cyber expertise into the acquisition workforce. This includes
embedding knowledgeable personnel - aka Cyber Focus Teams - within DAF PAE Offices and PMOs, and equipping them with expertise and resources to enhance
the cyber posture of DAF weapon systems. The activity also includes funding capabilities to enable effective sharing of classified cyber intelligence and vulnerability
information across multiple acquisition programs, identifying technologies, tactics, and policies for further development, prototyping, and supporting operational exercises
to posture DAF weapon systems to counter emerging threats. Furthermore, this activity includes organization and analysis of the DAF's cyber risk and mitigations
landscape to equip senior leaders with the most up to date knowledge of force posture and inform investment strategies. Another noteworthy activity enables the
CROWS to centralize and consolidate DAF and Department of War acquisition cyber needs and conduct threat-informed weapon systems solution analysis, identify and
prioritize vulnerabilities, and deliver courses of action to mature the materiel and non-materiel solutions for mitigated vulnerabilities.

In FY 2027, the entirety of project 642834, Mitigations, was transferred to project 642812, Acquisitions/System Security Engineering. This is an administrative
realignment to better highlight the synergy between the two activities and does not represent an increase or decrease in priority relative to the overall program.

This program element included all necessary expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds would be in
addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605833F, and 0605898F.



